# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: amino-acid
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:amino-acid/1-aminocyclopropane-1-carboxylic-acid] ACC is the precursor to the plant hormone ethylene.
[src:amino-acid/1-aminocyclopropane-1-carboxylic-acid] It is synthesized by the enzyme ACC synthase (EC 4.4.1.14) from methionine and converted to ethylene by ACC oxidase (EC 1.14.17.4).
[src:amino-acid/1-aminocyclopropane-1-carboxylic-acid] ACC also exhibits ethylene-independent signaling that plays a critical role in pollination and seed production by activating proteins similar to those involved in nervous system responses in humans and animals.
[src:amino-acid/1-aminocyclopropane-1-carboxylic-acid] More specifically, ACC signaling promotes secretion of the pollen tube chemoattractant LURE1.2 in ovular sporophytic tissue thus enhancing pollen tube attraction.
[src:amino-acid/1-aminocyclopropane-1-carboxylic-acid] Additionally, ACC activates Ca2+-containing ion currents via glutamate receptor-like (GLR) channels in root protoplasts.
[src:amino-acid/1-aminocyclopropane-1-carboxylic-acid] ACC can be used by soil microorganisms (both bacteria and fungi) as a source of nitrogen and carbon.
[src:amino-acid/1-aminocyclopropane-1-carboxylic-acid] As such, using ACC to incubate soils has been proven to induce the gene abundance encoding ACC-deaminases, which may have positive consequences on plant growth and stress tolerance.
[src:amino-acid/1-aminocyclopropane-1-carboxylic-acid] ACC is also an exogenous partial agonist of the mammalian NMDA receptor.
[src:amino-acid/1-aminocyclopropane-1-carboxylic-acid] In 2019, the United States Environmental Protection Agency issued notice of an application for an experimental use permit to be issued for use of ACC as a pesticide.
[src:amino-acid/1-pyrroline-5-carboxylate-dehydrogenase] The three substrates of this enzyme are (*S*)-1-pyrroline-5-carboxylate, nicotinamide adenine dinucleotide (NAD+), and water.
[src:amino-acid/1-pyrroline-5-carboxylate-dehydrogenase] The starting material is in chemical equilibrium with L-glutamate-5-semialdehyde, which is oxidised to L-glutamic acid, giving reduced NADH, and a proton.
[src:amino-acid/1-pyrroline-5-carboxylate-dehydrogenase] This enzyme belongs to the family of oxidoreductases, specifically those acting on the CH-NH group of donors with NAD+ or NADP+ as acceptor.
[src:amino-acid/1-pyrroline-5-carboxylate-dehydrogenase] The systematic name of this enzyme class is **(*S*)-1-pyrroline-5-carboxylate:NAD+ oxidoreductase**.
[src:amino-acid/1-pyrroline-5-carboxylate-dehydrogenase] This enzyme participates in glutamate metabolism and arginine and proline metabolism.
[src:amino-acid/1-pyrroline-5-carboxylate-dehydrogenase] As of late 2007, 14 structures have been solved for this class of enzymes, with PDB accession codes PDB: 2BHP, PDB: 2BHQ, PDB: 2BJA, PDB: 2BJK, PDB: 2EHQ, PDB: 2EHU, PDB: 2EII, PDB: 2EIT, PDB: 2EIW, PDB: 2EJ6, PDB: 2EJD, PDB: 2EJL, PDB: 2IY6, and PDB: 2J40.
[src:amino-acid/1-pyrroline-5-carboxylate-dehydrogenase] In human, the protein is encoded by *ALDH4A1* gene.
[src:amino-acid/2-aminoisobutyric-acid] 2-Aminoisobutyric acid can be prepared from acetone cyanohydrin, by reaction with ammonia followed by hydrolysis.
[src:amino-acid/2-aminoisobutyric-acid] The compound is not chiral, unlike most amino acids.
[src:amino-acid/2-aminoisobutyric-acid] It is a strong helix inducer in peptides due to Thorpe–Ingold effect of its gem-dimethyl group.
[src:amino-acid/2-aminoisobutyric-acid] 2-Aminoisobutyric acid is not one of the proteinogenic amino acids and is rather rare in nature (*cf.* non-proteinogenic amino acids).
[src:amino-acid/2-aminoisobutyric-acid] In the context of cell-free protein synthesis 2-aminoisobutyric acid is compatible with ribosomal elongation of peptide synthesis.
[src:amino-acid/2-aminoisobutyric-acid] Flexizymes and an engineered tRNA body enhance the affinity of aminoacylated Aib-tRNA species to elongation factor P.
[src:amino-acid/2-aminoisobutyric-acid] The result was an increased incorporation of Aib into peptides in a cell free translation system.
[src:amino-acid/2-aminoisobutyric-acid] Iqbal *et al.*. used an alternative approach of creating an editing deficient valine—tRNA ligase to synthesize aminoacylated Aib-tRNAVal.
[src:amino-acid/2-aminoisobutyric-acid] The aminoacylated tRNA was subsequently used in a cell-free translation system to yield Aib-containing peptides.
[src:amino-acid/2-aminoisobutyric-acid] Aib has been found in meteorites and some antibiotics of fungal origin, such as alamethicin and some lantibiotics.
[src:amino-acid/2-aminothiazoline-4-carboxylic-acid] It is produced by the reaction of methyl chloroacrylate with thiourea.
[src:amino-acid/2-aminothiazoline-4-carboxylic-acid] It is also a biomarker for cyanide poisoning, as it results from the condensation of cysteine and cyanide.
[src:amino-acid/3-hydroxy-2-methylbutyryl-coa-dehydrogenase] The two substrates of this enzyme are (2*S*,3*S*)-2-methyl-3-hydroxybutyryrl-CoA and oxidised nicotinamide adenine dinucleotide (NAD+).
[src:amino-acid/3-hydroxy-2-methylbutyryl-coa-dehydrogenase] Its products are 2-methylacetoacetyl-CoA, reduced NADH, and a proton.
[src:amino-acid/3-hydroxy-2-methylbutyryl-coa-dehydrogenase] This enzyme belongs to the family of oxidoreductases, specifically those acting on the CH-OH group of donor with NAD+ or NADP+ as acceptor.
[src:amino-acid/3-hydroxy-2-methylbutyryl-coa-dehydrogenase] The systematic name of this enzyme class is **(2S,3S)-3-hydroxy-2-methylbutanoyl-CoA:NAD+ oxidoreductase**.
[src:amino-acid/3-hydroxy-2-methylbutyryl-coa-dehydrogenase] Other names in common use include **2-methyl-3-hydroxybutyryl coenzyme A dehydrogenase**, **2-methyl-3-hydroxybutyryl coenzyme A dehydrogenase**, and **2-methyl-3-hydroxy-butyryl CoA dehydrogenase**.
[src:amino-acid/3-hydroxy-2-methylbutyryl-coa-dehydrogenase] This enzyme participates in valine, leucine and isoleucine degradation.
[src:amino-acid/3-hydroxy-2-methylbutyryl-coa-dehydrogenase] As of 20 January 2010, 6 structure have been solved for this class of enzymes, with the PDB accession code PDB: 1E3S, PDB: 1E3W, PDB: 1E6W, PDB: 1SO8, PDB: 1U7T, PDB: 2O23.
[src:amino-acid/3-hydroxybutyryl-coa-dehydrogenase] The two substrates of this enzyme are β-hydroxybutyryl-CoA and oxidised nicotinamide adenine dinucleotide phosphate (NADP+).
[src:amino-acid/3-hydroxybutyryl-coa-dehydrogenase] Its products are acetoacetyl-CoA, reduced NADPH, and a proton.
[src:amino-acid/3-hydroxybutyryl-coa-dehydrogenase] This enzyme belongs to the family of oxidoreductases, to be specific those acting on the CH-OH group of donor with NAD+ or NADP+ as acceptor.
[src:amino-acid/3-hydroxybutyryl-coa-dehydrogenase] The systematic name of this enzyme class is **(*S*)-3-hydroxybutanoyl-CoA:NADP+ oxidoreductase**.
[src:amino-acid/3-hydroxybutyryl-coa-dehydrogenase] This enzyme participates in benzoate degradation via coa ligation and butanoate metabolism.
[src:amino-acid/3-methoxytyramine] 3-Methoxytyramine occurs naturally in the prickly pear cactus (genus *Opuntia*), and is in general widespread throughout the Cactaceae.
[src:amino-acid/3-methoxytyramine] It has also been found in crown gall tumors on *Nicotiana* sp.
[src:amino-acid/3-methoxytyramine] In humans, 3-methoxytyramine is a trace amine that occurs as a metabolite of dopamine.
[src:amino-acid/3-methoxytyramine] Originally thought to be physiologically inactive, 3-MT was subsequently found to act as an agonist of the rodent and human TAAR1.
[src:amino-acid/3-methoxytyramine] 3-MT can induce weak hyperlocomotion in mice and this effect is partially attenuated in TAAR1 knockout mice.
[src:amino-acid/amino-acid] Amino acids can be classified according to the locations of the core structural functional groups (alpha- (α-), beta- (β-), gamma- (γ-) amino acids, etc.); other categories relate to polarity, ionization, and side-chain group type (aliphatic, acyclic, aromatic, polar, etc.).
[src:amino-acid/amino-acid] In the form of proteins, amino-acid *residues* form the second-largest component (water being the largest) of human muscles and other tissues.
[src:amino-acid/amino-acid] Beyond their role as residues in proteins, amino acids participate in a number of processes such as neurotransmitter transport and biosynthesis.
[src:amino-acid/amino-acid] It is thought that they played a key role in enabling life on Earth and its emergence.
[src:amino-acid/amino-acid] Amino acids are formally named by the IUPAC-IUBMB Joint Commission on Biochemical Nomenclature in terms of the fictitious "neutral" structure shown in the illustration.
[src:amino-acid/amino-acid] For example, the systematic name of alanine is 2-aminopropanoic acid, based on the formula CH3−CH(NH2)−COOH.
[src:amino-acid/amino-acid] The first few amino acids were discovered in the early 1800s.
[src:amino-acid/amino-acid] In 1806, French chemists Louis-Nicolas Vauquelin and Pierre Jean Robiquet isolated a compound from asparagus that was subsequently named asparagine, the first amino acid to be discovered.
[src:amino-acid/amino-acid] Cystine was discovered in 1810, although its monomer, cysteine, remained undiscovered until 1884.
[src:amino-acid/amino-acid] Glycine and leucine were discovered in 1820.
[src:amino-acid/amino-acid] The last of the 20 common amino acids to be discovered was threonine in 1935 by William Cumming Rose, who also determined the essential amino acids and established the minimum daily requirements of all amino acids for optimal growth.
[src:amino-acid/amino-acid] The unity of the chemical category was recognized by Wurtz in 1865, but he gave no particular name to it.
[src:amino-acid/amino-acid] The first use of the term "amino acid" in the English language dates from 1898, while the German term, *Aminosäure*, was used earlier.
[src:amino-acid/amino-acid] Proteins were found to yield amino acids after enzymatic digestion or acid hydrolysis.
[src:amino-acid/amino-acid] In 1902, Emil Fischer and Franz Hofmeister independently proposed that proteins are formed from many amino acids, whereby bonds are formed between the amino group of one amino acid with the carboxyl group of another, resulting in a linear structure that Fischer termed "peptide".
[src:amino-acid/amino-acid] 2-, alpha-, or α-amino acids have the generic formula H2NCHRCOOH in most cases, where R is an organic substituent known as a "side chain".
[src:amino-acid/amino-acid] Of the many hundreds of described amino acids, 22 are proteinogenic ("protein-building").
[src:amino-acid/amino-acid] It is these 22 compounds that combine to give a vast array of peptides and proteins assembled by ribosomes.
[src:amino-acid/amino-acid] Non-proteinogenic amino acids may arise through nonribosomal peptide synthesis.
[src:amino-acid/amino-acid] Modified amino acids, by contrast, typically result from post-translational modification.
[src:amino-acid/amino-acid] Amino acids with the structure NH+3−CXY−CXY−CO−2, such as β-alanine, a component of carnosine and a few other peptides, are β-amino acids.
[src:amino-acid/amino-acid] Ones with the structure NH+3−CXY−CXY−CXY−CO−2 are γ-amino acids, and so on, where X and Y are two substituents (one of which is normally H).
[src:amino-acid/amino-acid] The carbon atom next to the carboxyl group is called the α–carbon.
[src:amino-acid/amino-acid] In proteinogenic amino acids, it bears the amine and the R group or side chain specific to each amino acid, as well as a hydrogen atom.
[src:amino-acid/amino-acid] With the exception of glycine, for which the side chain is also a hydrogen atom, the α–carbon is stereogenic.
[src:amino-acid/amino-acid] All chiral proteinogenic amino acids have the L configuration.
[src:amino-acid/amino-acid] They are "left-handed" enantiomers, which refers to the stereoisomers of the alpha carbon.
[src:amino-acid/amino-acid] A few D-amino acids ("right-handed") have been found in nature, e.g., in bacterial envelopes, as a neuromodulator (D-serine), and in some antibiotics.
[src:amino-acid/amino-acid] Rarely, D-amino acid residues are found in proteins, and are converted from the L-amino acid as a post-translational modification.
[src:amino-acid/amino-acid] Five amino acids possess a charge at neutral pH.
[src:amino-acid/amino-acid] Often these side chains appear at the surfaces on proteins to enable their solubility in water, and side chains with opposite charges form important electrostatic contacts called salt bridges that maintain structures within a single protein or between interfacing proteins.
[src:amino-acid/amino-acid] Many proteins bind metal into their structures specifically, and these interactions are commonly mediated by charged side chains such as aspartate, glutamate and histidine.
[src:amino-acid/amino-acid] Under certain conditions, each ion-forming group can be charged, forming double salts.
[src:amino-acid/amino-acid] The two negatively charged amino acids at neutral pH are aspartate (Asp, D) and glutamate (Glu, E).
[src:amino-acid/amino-acid] The anionic carboxylate groups behave as Brønsted bases in most circumstances.
[src:amino-acid/amino-acid] Enzymes in very low pH environments, like the aspartic protease pepsin in mammalian stomachs, may have catalytic aspartate or glutamate residues that act as Brønsted acids.
[src:amino-acid/amino-acid] There are three amino acids with side chains that are cations at neutral pH: arginine (Arg, R), lysine (Lys, K) and histidine (His, H).
[src:amino-acid/amino-acid] Arginine has a charged guanidino group and lysine a charged alkyl amino group, and are fully protonated at pH 7.
[src:amino-acid/amino-acid] Histidine's imidazole group has a pKa of 6.0, and is only around 10% protonated at neutral pH.
[src:amino-acid/amino-acid] Because histidine is easily found in its basic and conjugate acid forms it often participates in catalytic proton transfers in enzyme reactions.
[src:amino-acid/amino-acid] The polar, uncharged amino acids serine (Ser, S), threonine (Thr, T), asparagine (Asn, N) and glutamine (Gln, Q) readily form hydrogen bonds with water and other amino acids.
[src:amino-acid/amino-acid] They do not ionize in normal conditions, a prominent exception being the catalytic serine in serine proteases.
[src:amino-acid/amino-acid] This is an example of severe perturbation, and is not characteristic of serine residues in general.
[src:amino-acid/amino-acid] Threonine has two chiral centers, not only the L (2*S*) chiral center at the α-carbon shared by all amino acids apart from achiral glycine, but also (3*R*) at the β-carbon.
[src:amino-acid/amino-acid] The full stereochemical specification is (2*S*,3*R*)-L-threonine.
[src:amino-acid/amino-acid] Because of the presence of phenolic hydroxyl group with a pKa = ~10, tyrosine is best classified as a neutral polar amino acid, but with amphipathic character that makes it less polar than classical small polar amino acid residues.
[src:amino-acid/amino-acid] Nonpolar amino acid interactions are the primary driving force behind the processes that fold proteins into their functional three dimensional structures.
[src:amino-acid/amino-acid] None of these amino acids' side chains ionize easily, and therefore do not have pKas.
[src:amino-acid/amino-acid] Several side chains are not described well by the charged, polar and hydrophobic categories.
[src:amino-acid/amino-acid] Glycine (Gly, G) could be considered a polar amino acid since its small size means that its solubility is largely determined by the amino and carboxylate groups.
[src:amino-acid/amino-acid] However, the lack of any side chain provides glycine with a unique flexibility among amino acids with large ramifications to protein folding.
[src:amino-acid/amino-acid] Cysteine (Cys, C) can also form hydrogen bonds readily, which would place it in the polar amino acid category, though it can often be found in protein structures forming covalent bonds, called disulphide bonds, with other cysteines.
[src:amino-acid/amino-acid] These bonds influence the folding and stability of proteins, and are essential in the formation of antibodies.
[src:amino-acid/amino-acid] Proline (Pro, P) has an alkyl side chain and could be considered hydrophobic, but because the side chain joins back onto the alpha amino group it becomes particularly inflexible when incorporated into proteins.
[src:amino-acid/amino-acid] Similar to glycine this influences protein structure in a way unique among amino acids.
[src:amino-acid/amino-acid] Selenocysteine (Sec, U) is a rare amino acid not directly encoded by DNA, but is incorporated into proteins via the ribosome.
[src:amino-acid/amino-acid] Selenocysteine has a lower redox potential compared to the similar cysteine, and participates in several unique enzymatic reactions.
[src:amino-acid/amino-acid] Pyrrolysine (Pyl, O) is another amino acid not encoded in DNA, but synthesized into protein by ribosomes.
[src:amino-acid/amino-acid] It is found in archaeal species where it participates in the catalytic activity of several methyltransferases.
[src:amino-acid/amino-acid] The 20 canonical amino acids can be classified according to their properties.
[src:amino-acid/amino-acid] Important factors are charge, hydrophilicity or hydrophobicity, size, and functional groups.
[src:amino-acid/amino-acid] These properties influence protein structure and protein–protein interactions.
[src:amino-acid/amino-acid] The water-soluble proteins tend to have their hydrophobic residues (Leu, Ile, Val, Phe, and Trp) buried in the middle of the protein, whereas hydrophilic side chains are exposed to the aqueous solvent.
[src:amino-acid/amino-acid] (In biochemistry, a residue refers to a specific monomer *within* the polymeric chain of a polysaccharide, protein or nucleic acid.) The integral membrane proteins tend to have outer rings of exposed hydrophobic amino acids that anchor them in the lipid bilayer.
[src:amino-acid/amino-acid] Some peripheral membrane proteins have a patch of hydrophobic amino acids on their surface that sticks to the membrane.
[src:amino-acid/amino-acid] In a similar fashion, proteins that have to bind to positively charged molecules have surfaces rich in negatively charged amino acids such as glutamate and aspartate, while proteins binding to negatively charged molecules have surfaces rich in positively charged amino acids like lysine and arginine.
[src:amino-acid/amino-acid] For example, lysine and arginine are present in large amounts in the low-complexity regions of nucleic-acid binding proteins.
[src:amino-acid/amino-acid] There are various hydrophobicity scales of amino acid residues.
[src:amino-acid/amino-acid] Some amino acids have special properties.
[src:amino-acid/amino-acid] Cysteine can form covalent disulfide bonds to other cysteine residues.
[src:amino-acid/amino-acid] Proline forms a cycle to the polypeptide backbone, and glycine is more flexible than other amino acids.
[src:amino-acid/amino-acid] Glycine and proline are strongly present within low complexity regions of both eukaryotic and prokaryotic proteins, whereas the opposite is the case with cysteine, phenylalanine, tryptophan, methionine, valine, leucine, isoleucine, which are highly reactive, or complex, or hydrophobic.
[src:amino-acid/amino-acid] For example, a signaling protein can attach and then detach from a cell membrane, because it contains cysteine residues that can have the fatty acid palmitic acid added to them and subsequently removed.
[src:amino-acid/amino-acid] The common natural forms of amino acids have a zwitterionic structure, with −NH+3 (−NH+2− in the case of proline) and −CO−2 functional groups attached to the same C atom, and are thus α-amino acids, and are the only ones found in proteins during translation in the ribosome.
[src:amino-acid/amino-acid] In aqueous solution at pH close to neutrality, amino acids are energetically favored in their zwitterionic form, with a deprotonated CO−2 group and a protonated NH+3 group, because the high dielectric constant of water and its hydrogen-bonding network effectively stabilize separated charges.
[src:amino-acid/amino-acid] Thus, the overall structure is NH+3−CHR−CO−2, and the so-called "neutral forms" −NH2−CHR−CO2H are not present to any measurable degree at physiological pH.
[src:amino-acid/amino-acid] In strongly acidic conditions (pH below 3), the carboxylate group becomes protonated and the structure becomes an ammonio carboxylic acid, NH+3−CHR−CO2H.
[src:amino-acid/amino-acid] This is relevant for enzymes like pepsin that are active in acidic environments such as the mammalian stomach and lysosomes, but does not significantly apply to intracellular enzymes.
[src:amino-acid/amino-acid] In highly basic conditions (pH greater than 10, not normally seen in physiological conditions), the ammonio group is deprotonated to give NH2−CHR−CO−2.
[src:amino-acid/amino-acid] Although various definitions of acids and bases are used in chemistry, the only one that is useful for chemistry in aqueous solution is that of Brønsted: an acid is a species that can donate a proton to another species, and a base is one that can accept a proton.
[src:amino-acid/amino-acid] This criterion is used to label the groups in the above illustration.
[src:amino-acid/amino-acid] The carboxylate side chains of aspartate and glutamate residues are the principal Brønsted bases in proteins.
[src:amino-acid/amino-acid] Likewise, lysine, tyrosine and cysteine will typically act as a Brønsted acid.
[src:amino-acid/amino-acid] Histidine under these conditions can act both as a Brønsted acid and a base.
[src:amino-acid/amino-acid] For amino acids with uncharged side-chains the zwitterion predominates at pH values between the two p*K*a values, but coexists in equilibrium with small amounts of net negative and net positive ions.
[src:amino-acid/amino-acid] At the midpoint between the two p*K*a values, the trace amount of net negative and trace of net positive ions balance, so that average net charge of all forms present is zero.
[src:amino-acid/amino-acid] This pH is known as the isoelectric point p*I*, so p*I* = ⁠1/2⁠(p*K*a1 + p*K*a2).
[src:amino-acid/amino-acid] For amino acids with charged side chains, the p*K*a of the side chain is involved.
[src:amino-acid/amino-acid] Thus for aspartate or glutamate with negative side chains, the terminal amino group is essentially entirely in the charged form −NH+3, but this positive charge needs to be balanced by the state with just one C-terminal carboxylate group is negatively charged.
[src:amino-acid/amino-acid] This occurs halfway between the two carboxylate p*K*a values: p*I* = ⁠1/2⁠(p*K*a1 + p*K*a(R)), where p*K*a(R) is the side chain p*K*a.
[src:amino-acid/amino-acid] Similar considerations apply to other amino acids with ionizable side-chains, including not only glutamate (similar to aspartate), but also cysteine, histidine, lysine, tyrosine and arginine with positive side chains.
[src:amino-acid/amino-acid] Amino acids have zero mobility in electrophoresis at their isoelectric point, although this behaviour is more usually exploited for peptides and proteins than single amino acids.
[src:amino-acid/amino-acid] Zwitterionic amino acids exhibit minimal solubility at their isoelectric point, and in some cases can be isolated from aqueous solution by adjusting the pH to the appropriate isoelectric value.
[src:amino-acid/amino-acid] Although one-letter symbols are included in the table, IUPAC–IUBMB recommend that "Use of the one-letter symbols should be restricted to the comparison of long sequences".
[src:amino-acid/amino-acid] In addition to the specific amino acid codes, placeholders are used in cases where chemical or crystallographic analysis of a peptide or protein cannot conclusively determine the identity of a residue.
[src:amino-acid/amino-acid] They are also used to summarize conserved protein sequence motifs.
[src:amino-acid/amino-acid] The use of single letters to indicate sets of similar residues is similar to the use of abbreviation codes for degenerate bases.
[src:amino-acid/amino-acid] In addition, many nonstandard amino acids have a specific code.
[src:amino-acid/amino-acid] For example, several peptide drugs, such as Bortezomib and MG132, are artificially synthesized and retain their protecting groups, which have specific codes.
[src:amino-acid/amino-acid] Bortezomib is Pyz–Phe–boroLeu, and MG132 is Z–Leu–Leu–Leu–al.
[src:amino-acid/amino-acid] To aid in the analysis of protein structure, photo-reactive amino acid analogs are available.
[src:amino-acid/amino-acid] These include photoleucine (**pLeu**) and photomethionine (**pMet**).
[src:amino-acid/amino-acid] Amino acids are the precursors to proteins.
[src:amino-acid/amino-acid] They join by condensation reactions to form short polymer chains called peptides or longer chains called either polypeptides or proteins.
[src:amino-acid/amino-acid] These chains are linear and unbranched, with each amino acid residue within the chain attached to two neighboring amino acids.
[src:amino-acid/amino-acid] In nature, the process of making proteins encoded by RNA genetic material is called *translation* and involves the step-by-step addition of amino acids to a growing protein chain by a ribozyme that is called a ribosome.
[src:amino-acid/amino-acid] The order in which the amino acids are added is read through the genetic code from an mRNA template, which is an RNA derived from one of the organism's genes.
[src:amino-acid/amino-acid] There are 22 amino acids that get naturally incorporated into polypeptides; these are called *proteinogenic amino acids* or *natural amino acids*.
[src:amino-acid/amino-acid] Of these, 20 are encoded by the universal genetic code.
[src:amino-acid/amino-acid] The remaining 2, selenocysteine and pyrrolysine, are incorporated into proteins by unique synthetic mechanisms.
[src:amino-acid/amino-acid] Selenocysteine is incorporated when the mRNA being translated includes a SECIS element, which causes the UGA codon to encode selenocysteine instead of a stop codon.
[src:amino-acid/amino-acid] Pyrrolysine is used by some methanogenic archaea in enzymes that they use to produce methane.
[src:amino-acid/amino-acid] It is coded for with the codon UAG, which is normally a stop codon in other organisms.
[src:amino-acid/amino-acid] The 20 amino acids that are encoded directly by the codons of the universal genetic code are called *standard* or *canonical* amino acids.
[src:amino-acid/amino-acid] A modified form of methionine (*N*-formylmethionine) is often incorporated in place of methionine as the initial amino acid of proteins in bacteria, mitochondria and plastids (including chloroplasts).
[src:amino-acid/amino-acid] Other amino acids are called *nonstandard* or *non-canonical*.
[src:amino-acid/amino-acid] Most of the nonstandard amino acids are also non-proteinogenic (i.e. they cannot be incorporated into proteins during translation), but two of them are proteinogenic, as they can be incorporated translationally into proteins by exploiting information not encoded in the universal genetic code.
[src:amino-acid/amino-acid] The two nonstandard proteinogenic amino acids are selenocysteine (present in many non-eukaryotes as well as most eukaryotes, but not coded directly by DNA) and pyrrolysine (found only in some archaea and at least one bacterium).
[src:amino-acid/amino-acid] The incorporation of these nonstandard amino acids is rare.
[src:amino-acid/amino-acid] For example, 25 human proteins include selenocysteine in their primary structure, and the structurally characterized enzymes (selenoenzymes) employ selenocysteine as the catalytic moiety in their active sites.
[src:amino-acid/amino-acid] Pyrrolysine and selenocysteine are encoded via variant codons.
[src:amino-acid/amino-acid] For example, selenocysteine is encoded by stop codon and SECIS element.
[src:amino-acid/amino-acid] Aside from the 22 proteinogenic amino acids, many *non-proteinogenic* amino acids are known.
[src:amino-acid/amino-acid] These either are not found in proteins (for example carnitine, GABA, ornithine) or are not produced directly and in isolation by standard cellular machinery.
[src:amino-acid/amino-acid] For example, hydroxyproline is synthesized from proline, and selenomethionine is produced by metabolic modification of methionine.
[src:amino-acid/amino-acid] Non-proteinogenic amino acids that are found in proteins are formed by post-translational modification.
[src:amino-acid/amino-acid] Such modifications can also determine the localization of the protein, e.g., the addition of long hydrophobic groups can cause a protein to bind to a phospholipid membrane.
[src:amino-acid/amino-acid] Some non-proteinogenic amino acids are not found in proteins.
[src:amino-acid/amino-acid] Examples include 2-aminoisobutyric acid and the neurotransmitter gamma-aminobutyric acid.
[src:amino-acid/amino-acid] Non-proteinogenic amino acids often occur as intermediates in the metabolic pathways for standard amino acids – for example, ornithine and citrulline occur in the urea cycle, part of amino acid catabolism (see below).
[src:amino-acid/amino-acid] A rare exception to the dominance of α-amino acids in biology is the β-amino acid beta alanine (3-aminopropanoic acid), which is used in plants and microorganisms in the synthesis of pantothenic acid (vitamin B5), a component of coenzyme A.
[src:amino-acid/amino-acid] Many proteinogenic and non-proteinogenic amino acids have biological functions beyond being precursors to proteins and peptides.
[src:amino-acid/amino-acid] In humans, amino acids also have important roles in diverse biosynthetic pathways.
[src:amino-acid/amino-acid] Defenses against herbivores in plants sometimes employ amino acids.
[src:amino-acid/amino-acid] However, not all of the functions of other abundant nonstandard amino acids are known.
[src:amino-acid/amino-acid] Animals ingest amino acids in the form of protein.
[src:amino-acid/amino-acid] The protein is broken down into its constituent amino acids in the process of digestion.
[src:amino-acid/amino-acid] The amino acids are then used to synthesize new proteins and other nitrogenous biomolecules, or they are further catabolized through oxidation to provide a source of energy.
[src:amino-acid/amino-acid] The oxidation pathway starts with the removal of the amino group by a transaminase; the amino group is then fed into the urea cycle.
[src:amino-acid/amino-acid] The other product of transamidation is a keto acid that enters the citric acid cycle.
[src:amino-acid/amino-acid] Glucogenic amino acids can also be converted into glucose, through gluconeogenesis.
[src:amino-acid/amino-acid] Of the 20 standard amino acids, nine (His, Ile, Leu, Lys, Met, Phe, Thr, Trp and Val) are called essential amino acids because the human body cannot synthesize them from other compounds at the level needed for normal growth, so they must be obtained from food.
[src:amino-acid/amino-acid] In addition, cysteine, tyrosine, and arginine are considered semiessential amino acids, and taurine a semi-essential aminosulfonic acid in children.
[src:amino-acid/amino-acid] Some amino acids are conditionally essential for certain ages or medical conditions.
[src:amino-acid/amino-acid] Essential amino acids may also vary from species to species.
[src:amino-acid/amino-acid] The metabolic pathways that synthesize these monomers are not fully developed.
[src:amino-acid/amino-acid] Amino acids are sometimes added to animal feed because some of the components of these feeds, such as soybeans, have low levels of some of the essential amino acids, especially of lysine, methionine, threonine, and tryptophan.
[src:amino-acid/amino-acid] Likewise amino acids are used to chelate metal cations in order to improve the absorption of minerals from feed supplements.
[src:amino-acid/amino-acid] The food industry is a major consumer of amino acids, especially glutamic acid, which is used as a flavor enhancer, and aspartame (aspartylphenylalanine 1-methyl ester), which is used as an artificial sweetener.
[src:amino-acid/amino-acid] Amino acids are sometimes added to food by manufacturers to alleviate symptoms of mineral deficiencies, such as anemia, by improving mineral absorption and reducing negative side effects from inorganic mineral supplementation.
[src:amino-acid/amino-acid] Amino acids are low-cost feedstocks used in chiral pool synthesis as enantiomerically pure building blocks.
[src:amino-acid/amino-acid] Amino acids are used in the synthesis of some cosmetics.
[src:amino-acid/amino-acid] The chelating ability of amino acids is sometimes used in fertilizers to facilitate the delivery of minerals to plants in order to correct mineral deficiencies, such as iron chlorosis.
[src:amino-acid/amino-acid] These fertilizers are also used to prevent deficiencies from occurring and to improve the overall health of the plants.
[src:amino-acid/amino-acid] Amino acids have been considered as components of biodegradable polymers, which have applications as environmentally friendly packaging and in medicine in drug delivery and the construction of prosthetic implants.
[src:amino-acid/amino-acid] An interesting example of such materials is polyaspartate, a water-soluble biodegradable polymer that may have applications in disposable diapers and agriculture.
[src:amino-acid/amino-acid] Due to its solubility and ability to chelate metal ions, polyaspartate is also being used as a biodegradable antiscaling agent and a corrosion inhibitor.
[src:amino-acid/amino-acid] The commercial production of amino acids usually relies on mutant bacteria that overproduce individual amino acids using glucose as a carbon source.
[src:amino-acid/amino-acid] Some amino acids are produced by enzymatic conversions of synthetic intermediates.
[src:amino-acid/amino-acid] 2-Aminothiazoline-4-carboxylic acid is an intermediate in one industrial synthesis of L-cysteine for example.
[src:amino-acid/amino-acid] Aspartic acid is produced by the addition of ammonia to fumarate using a lyase.
[src:amino-acid/amino-acid] In plants, nitrogen is first assimilated into organic compounds in the form of glutamate, formed from alpha-ketoglutarate and ammonia in the mitochondrion.
[src:amino-acid/amino-acid] For other amino acids, plants use transaminases to move the amino group from glutamate to another alpha-keto acid.
[src:amino-acid/amino-acid] For example, aspartate aminotransferase converts glutamate and oxaloacetate to alpha-ketoglutarate and aspartate.
[src:amino-acid/amino-acid] Other organisms use transaminases for amino acid synthesis, too.
[src:amino-acid/amino-acid] Nonstandard amino acids are usually formed through modifications to standard amino acids.
[src:amino-acid/amino-acid] For example, homocysteine is formed through the transsulfuration pathway or by the demethylation of methionine via the intermediate metabolite *S*-adenosylmethionine, while hydroxyproline is made by a post translational modification of proline.
[src:amino-acid/amino-acid] Microorganisms and plants synthesize many uncommon amino acids.
[src:amino-acid/amino-acid] For example, some microbes make 2-aminoisobutyric acid and lanthionine, which is a sulfide-bridged derivative of alanine.
[src:amino-acid/amino-acid] Both of these amino acids are found in peptidic lantibiotics such as alamethicin.
[src:amino-acid/amino-acid] However, in plants, 1-aminocyclopropane-1-carboxylic acid is a small disubstituted cyclic amino acid that is an intermediate in the production of the plant hormone ethylene.
[src:amino-acid/amino-acid] The formation of amino acids and peptides is assumed to have preceded and perhaps induced the emergence of life on earth.
[src:amino-acid/amino-acid] Amino acids can form from simple precursors under various conditions.
[src:amino-acid/amino-acid] Surface-based chemical metabolism of amino acids and very small compounds may have led to the build-up of amino acids, coenzymes and phosphate-based small carbon molecules.
[src:amino-acid/amino-acid] Amino acids and similar building blocks could have been elaborated into proto-peptides, with peptides being considered key players in the origin of life.
[src:amino-acid/amino-acid] In the famous Urey-Miller experiment, the passage of an electric arc through a mixture of methane, hydrogen, and ammonia produces a large number of amino acids.
[src:amino-acid/amino-acid] Several hypotheses invoke the Strecker synthesis whereby hydrogen cyanide, simple aldehydes, ammonia, and water produce amino acids.
[src:amino-acid/amino-acid] According to a review, amino acids, and even peptides, "turn up fairly regularly in the various experimental broths that have been allowed to be cooked from simple chemicals.
[src:amino-acid/amino-acid] This is because nucleotides are far more difficult to synthesize chemically than amino acids." For a chronological order, it suggests that there must have been a 'protein world' or at least a 'polypeptide world', possibly later followed by the 'RNA world' and the 'DNA world'.
[src:amino-acid/amino-acid] Codon–amino acids mappings may be the biological information system at the primordial origin of life on Earth.
[src:amino-acid/amino-acid] While amino acids and consequently simple peptides must have formed under different experimentally probed geochemical scenarios, the transition from an abiotic world to the first life forms is to a large extent still unresolved.
[src:amino-acid/amino-acid] Amino acids undergo the reactions expected of the constituent functional groups.
[src:amino-acid/amino-acid] As both the amine and carboxylic acid groups of amino acids can react to form amide bonds, one amino acid molecule can react with another and become joined through an amide linkage.
[src:amino-acid/amino-acid] This polymerization of amino acids is what creates proteins.
[src:amino-acid/amino-acid] This condensation reaction yields the newly formed peptide bond and a molecule of water.
[src:amino-acid/amino-acid] In cells, this reaction does not occur directly; instead, the amino acid is first activated by attachment to a transfer RNA molecule through an ester bond.
[src:amino-acid/amino-acid] This aminoacyl-tRNA is produced in an ATP-dependent reaction carried out by an aminoacyl tRNA synthetase.
[src:amino-acid/amino-acid] This aminoacyl-tRNA is then a substrate for the ribosome, which catalyzes the attack of the amino group of the elongating protein chain on the ester bond.
[src:amino-acid/amino-acid] As a result of this mechanism, all proteins made by ribosomes are synthesized starting at their *N*-terminus and moving toward their *C*-terminus.
[src:amino-acid/amino-acid] However, not all peptide bonds are formed in this way.
[src:amino-acid/amino-acid] In a few cases, peptides are synthesized by specific enzymes.
[src:amino-acid/amino-acid] For example, the tripeptide glutathione is an essential part of the defenses of cells against oxidative stress.
[src:amino-acid/amino-acid] This peptide is synthesized in two steps from free amino acids.
[src:amino-acid/amino-acid] In the first step, gamma-glutamylcysteine synthetase condenses cysteine and glutamate through a peptide bond formed between the side chain carboxyl of the glutamate (the gamma carbon of this side chain) and the amino group of the cysteine.
[src:amino-acid/amino-acid] This dipeptide is then condensed with glycine by glutathione synthetase to form glutathione.
[src:amino-acid/amino-acid] In chemistry, peptides are synthesized by a variety of reactions.
[src:amino-acid/amino-acid] One of the most-used in solid-phase peptide synthesis uses the aromatic oxime derivatives of amino acids as activated units.
[src:amino-acid/amino-acid] These are added in sequence onto the growing peptide chain, which is attached to a solid resin support.
[src:amino-acid/amino-acid] Libraries of peptides are used in drug discovery through high-throughput screening.
[src:amino-acid/amino-acid] The combination of functional groups allow amino acids to be effective polydentate ligands for metal–amino acid chelates.
[src:amino-acid/amino-acid] The side chains of amino acids can also undergo posttranslational chemical reactions.
[src:amino-acid/amino-acid] Degradation of an amino acid often begins with transamination, in which its amino group is transferred to α-ketoglutarate, forming glutamate.
[src:amino-acid/amino-acid] This process involves transaminases, often the same enzymes used in amino acid synthesis.
[src:amino-acid/amino-acid] In many vertebrates, the amino group is subsequently released as ammonia and converted to urea via the urea cycle for excretion.
[src:amino-acid/amino-acid] However, amino acid degradation can result in uric acid or ammonia instead, depending on the organism.
[src:amino-acid/amino-acid] For example, serine dehydratase converts serine directly to pyruvate and ammonia.
[src:amino-acid/amino-acid] Amino acids are bidentate ligands, forming transition metal amino acid complexes.
[src:amino-acid/amino-acid] The total nitrogen content of organic matter is mainly formed by the amino groups in proteins.
[src:amino-acid/amino-acid] The total Kjeldahl nitrogen (TKN) is a measure of nitrogen widely used in the analysis of (waste) water, soil, food, feed and organic matter in general.
[src:amino-acid/amino-acid] As the name suggests, the Kjeldahl method is applied.
